results.notes:
Fruiting from beneath our tar paper and bark barrier-not directly from bark chips.
Cap: wavy, umbonate. About 5-7cm in circumference. Brown, shiny, somewhat viscous. Gills: slightly decurrent into stem, light brown.
Spore print: light brown-like Agrocybe but less abundant print as A. praecox.
Stipe: very striate and twisted-nearly white in context, fibrous. Partial universal veil remnant midway up stem.
Odor: Spermatic, farinaceous.

Fruiting singularly.

Elevation: Sea level.

NOTES: We have multiple very large 2nd growth Douglas fir approximately 100 feet from where this was fruiting. Not directly fruiting from bark chips, rather, fruiting from roots beneath chips(under tar paper tarp covering). Caps have the look of Rozites(Cortinarius) caperata in shape(especially at maturity) but much darker in color. Initial gut reaction was either Agrocybe or Hebeloma when I began monitoring.

UPDATE ON 9/14/18: 11 months after observation while landscaping our yard and pulling up tarp/bark I found a mass of mycelium/hyphae balled together with roots from the nearby Rhododendron. Immediately went and made a quick sterile medium for inoculation(hydrogen peroxide/filtered watered) with rice and inoculated the mass-now residing in the refrigerator. Will see if in a few months this will flush out. Caps color, striate stems are identical to the original collection and were forming within inches of the original fruiting location. Now that I seeded the area with grass we will monitor for years to come in the Autumn/Fall and see if successive flushes will continue. See added images of the process in side bar.

Growing on a bed of mulch several yards away from the same white pine that is associated with my “granulatus” post from 4 years ago, obs 149419.
Pinkish-tan, slightly variegated caps with lots of gluten following the rains of today. The cap pellicle has a 1 mm overhang. No partial veil remnants or cottony appendiculate material seen anywhere on the cap margins. Yellow pores, exuding a cloudy whitish liquid. Whitish to pale yellow scruffy to squamulose stipes, especially in the upper half, with a smattering of small glandular dots here and there (in some fruiting bodies; other are devoid of them). White basal mycelium.
NH4OH = grayish on pellicle; purplish-pink on cap flesh. KOH = dark olive-brown on pellicle; dark purplish-pink, resolving to violet and then to grayish-fuscous on cap flesh.

Place: Lower Trenta valley, right bank of river SoÄa; between villages SoÄa and Trenta; near the trail to settlement Na skalah, East Julian Alps, PosoÄje, Slovenia EC.

Comments: Experts are able to resolve two varieties of this species: Lactarius blennius var. blennius and Lactarius blennius var. fluens. I was unable to assign this find to one of them. Following the key of Section 6 of Lactarius (Ref.: 2, p383) this find should be Lactarius blennius var. blennius based on piled dimension (3 – 7 cm for var. blennius contrary to 5 – 12 cm for var. fluens) or Lactarius blennius var. fluens based on strong production of milk (even in quite dry state!). Also variable hut color speaks for this variety. On the other hand, the absence of lighter, almost whitish hut edge speaks in favor of the first option. The only reliable microscopic trait (Ref.:8) – thickness of ixocutis – has not be used because of quite dry fruitbodies. Also, if one reads the description of both varieties in Ref. 9 the text is almost identical and the associated drawings definitely are such. Too hard a problem for me.

Description of the find: six or seven pilei present in an area of about 4 × 3 m; pilei diameter 4.5 – 7 cm, surface almost dry, only slightly sticky (found after a long period of dry weather) but leaf debris firmly stuck to the hut surface speaking in favor of presence of a distinctive ixocutis; trama and gills of about the same thickness; milk instant, abundant, white, after a longer time, when almost dry, it becomes greenish-gray; gills bruise slowly and mildly darken to brownish, otherwise the fruitbodies do not discolor when handled; stipe 3.5 – 4.6 cm long, 9 to 12 mm in diameter; only minutely sticky; SP abundant, light beige with slight yellow tint, oac851.
